al Song|Best Original Song]]\n| [[Randy Newman]] <small>(for \"I Can't Let You Throw Yourself Away\")</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[40th Golden Raspberry Awards|March 16, 2020]]\n| [[The Razzie Redeemer Award]]\n| [[Keanu Reeves]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"Razzies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.razzies.com/razz-newz.html|title=RAZZ NEWZ - The Razzies!|website=razzies.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2020 Kids' Choice Awards]]\n| [[Kids' Choice Award for Favorite Animated Movie|Favorite Animated Movie]]\n| ''Toy Story 4''\n| {{pending}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/avengers-end-game-leads-nickelodeons-kids-choice-awards-nominations-billie-eilish-taylor-swift-chance-the-rapper-full-list-1202859259/|title=Nickelodeon's Kids' Choice Awards Nominations: 'Avengers: Endgame' Leads \u2013 Deadline|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Favorite Male Voice from an Animated Movie \n| Tom Hanks\n| {{pending}}\n|}\n\n== Future ==\n\n=== Possible sequel ===\nIn May 2019, producer Mark Nielsen confirmed that Pixar will return its focus to making original films instead of  sequels after ''Toy Story 4'' for a while.<ref name=\"auto2\" /> On ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', Tom Hanks stated that the film would be the final film in the series. He said to [[Ellen DeGeneres]] that Tim Allen had \"warned him about the emotional final goodbye between their characters Woody and Buzz Lightyear in ''Toy Story 4''.\"<ref>{{cite web | title= Tim Allen Warned Tom Hanks About the Emotional Ending of 'Toy Story 4' | url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=34d6jg4W0Rc | website= YouTube | accessdate= May 23, 2019 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190523125423/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=34d6jg4W0Rc | archive-date= May 23, 2019 | url-status= live }}</ref> However, Nielsen did not rule out a possibility of a fifth film, stating, \"Every film we make, we treat it like it's the first and the last film we're ever going to make, so you force yourself to make it hold up. You don't get in over your skis. Whether there's another one? I don't know. If there is, it's tomorrow's problem.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Pixar Not Ruling Out Toy Story 5|url=https://comicbook.com/movies/2019/05/26/toy-story-4-end-disney-pixar-not-ruling-out-toy-story-5/|website=comicbook.com|accessdate=May 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527000622/https://comicbook.com/movies/2019/05/26/toy-story-4-end-disney-pixar-not-ruling-out-toy-story-5/|archive-date=May 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Short film ===\nA short film titled ''[[Toy Story (franchise)#Lamp Life|Lamp Life]]'' reveals Bo Peep's whereabouts between leaving and reuniting with Woody.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scribner |first1=Herb |title=Disney Plus has a trailer for a new \u2018Toy Story\u2019 short film |url=https://www.deseret.com/entertainment/2020/1/28/21080366/disney-plus-toy-story-short-film-animated-release-date |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=Deseret News |date=January 28, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The short was released on [[Disney+]] on January 31, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prudom |first1=Laura |title=Disney Plus' Lamp Life Sneak Peek: What Happened to Bo Peep Between Toy Story 2 and 4? - IGN |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/lamp-life-disney-plus-bo-peep-pixar-release-date-short-film |accessdate=January 31, 2020 |work=ign.com |date=January 29, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Series ===\n{{main|Forky Asks a Question}}\nA 10-episode short-form educational series, ''Forky Asks a Question'', debuted exclusively on the [[Disney+]] streaming service upon its launch on November 12, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/pixar-creating-forky-focused-short-films-disney/|title= Pixar Creating Forky-Focused Short Films For Disney|first= James|last= White|date= June 12, 2019|accessdate= June 17, 2019|work= [[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190618055127/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/pixar-creating-forky-focused-short-films-disney/|archive-date= June 18, 2019|url-status= live}}</ref> It focuses mainly on Forky, but other ''Toy Story'' characters such as Rex, Hamm, Trixie, Buttercup, and Mr. Pricklepants also make appearances.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official|https://movies.disney.com/toy-story-4}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt1979376}}\n* {{tcmdb title|2073297|Toy Story 4}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|toy_story_4}}\n\n{{Toy Story}}\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Pixar}}\n{{John Lasseter}}\n{{Andrew Stanton}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Awards for ''Toy Story 4''\n|list=\n{{Academy Award Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Animated Motion Picture}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Fantasy Film}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:2019 3D films]]\n[[Category:2019 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s sequel films]]\n[[Category:3D animated films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American road movies]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Animated buddy films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated romance films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about dolls]]\n[[Category:Films about toys]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Josh Cooley]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Randy Newman]]\n[[Category:Films set in amusement parks]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Pixar animated films]]\n[[Category:Sacrifices in fiction]]\n[[Category:Toy Story]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Broadcast Film Critics Association Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:2019 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Davide King", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toy_Story_4"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guernsey", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Guernsey}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Bailiwick of Guernsey\n| image =\n| caption =\n| map1 = Bailiwick of Guernsey coronavirus map.svg\n| places = \n| legend1 = {{Center|Map of confirmed cases as of 12 April 2020}}\n{{Block indent|\n{{legend|#710000|200+ confirmed cases }}\n{{legend|#ac0100|100\u2013199 confirmed cases }}\n{{legend|#db3938|50\u201399 confirmed cases }}\n{{legend|#f79898|10\u201349 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffd0d0|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#e0e0e0|No confirmed cases or no data}}|left = 3}}\n| map2 = File:Bailiwick of Guernsey coronavirus deaths map.svg\n| legend2 = {{Center|Map of deaths as of 12 April 2020}}\n{{Block indent|\n<!-- {{legend|#2c7fb8|20\u201349 deaths}}\n{{legend|#41b6c4|10\u201319 deaths}}-->\n{{legend|#7fcdbb|5\u20139 deaths}}\n{{legend|#c7e9b4|1\u20134 deaths}}\n{{legend|#e0e0e0|No deaths or no data}}|left = 3}}\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019]]<br/>(COVID-19)\n| virus_strain = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory<br/>syndrome coronavirus 2]]<br/>(SARS-CoV-2)\n| location = [[Bailiwick of Guernsey]]\n| first_case = Imported from [[Tenerife]], Spain\n| arrival_date = 9 March 2020<br/>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=9|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 218<ref name=\"channelislands\">{{cite news |title=Live updates: Number of Coronavirus cases in the Channel Islands |url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-12/live-updates-number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-the-channel-islands/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=itv.com |agency=ITV |publisher=ITV News |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"test results\"/>\n| recovery_cases = 48<ref name=\"test results\"/>\n| deaths = 6{{refn|group=note|Only includes confirmed COVID-19 deaths. The States of Guernsey report 'confirmed' and 'presumptive' COVID-19 deaths separately.}}<ref name=\"test results\"/>\n| website = {{url|https://covid19.gov.gg}}\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Bailiwick of Guernsey''' is part of an [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The first case in the [[Bailiwick of Guernsey|Bailiwick]] was confirmed on 9 March when a person tested positive in [[Guernsey]] after returning from [[Tenerife]],<ref name=\"firstcase\"/> and transmission within the Bailiwick was confirmed on 24 March.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/> As of 12 April, there have been 218 cases identified in the Bailiwick, all in Guernsey,{{refn|group=note|'Guernsey' refers to the entire jurisdiction of Guernsey, which includes the island of Guernsey as well as the three inhabited islands of [[Herm]], [[Jethou]] and [[Lihou]].}} and 6 people are confirmed to have died from the infection;{{refn|group=note|The States of Guernsey has also recorded (separately) 3 'presumptive' deaths presumed to be due to COVID-19.}} no cases have been reported in [[Sark]] or [[Alderney]].<ref name=\"test results\"/>\n\nThe response by the [[States of Guernsey]] has been led by the Civil Contingencies Authority (CCA)\u2014a senior cross-committee body responsible for coordinating actions in circumstances which present a serious risk to the health and welfare of the island\u2014chaired by [[Gavin St Pier]] and advised by the senior [[Policy and Resources Committee of Guernsey|Policy and Resources Committee]] (P&R) and the Committee for Health and Social Care (HSC). St Pier\u2014Guernsey's [[Policy and Resources Committee of Guernsey#List of heads of government of Guernsey|Chief Minister]]\u2014has compared the threat to public health from the pandemic and the restriction of personal liberties as a result of the government-imposed lockdown measures in the Bailiwick to that seen during the [[second world war]].<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Guernsey urges self-isolation with any symptoms |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-51818817?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world/europe/guernsey&link_location=live-reporting-story |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Strict new measures come into force from midnight tonight |url=https://www.gov.gg/covid19newmeasures |website=gov.gg |date=24 March 2020 |publisher=States of Guernsey}}</ref>\n\nEarly response measures focused on [[behaviour change (public health)|behaviour changing]] publicity; encouraging [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Hand washing|hand-washing]], [[Hygiene#Respiratory hygiene|respiratory hygiene]] and [[social distancing]] measures, and advising against non-essential travel. Following the first confirmed case in the Bailiwick, the CCA enacted the Emergency Powers (Coronavirus) (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Regulations 2020 on 17 March, a statutory instrument which enables the Medical Officer of Health to implement emergency measures enforceable by law; the first of which mandated that anyone arriving in the Bailiwick [[Isolation (health care)#Self-isolation|self-isolate]] for 14 days. Following the first confirmed case from on-island transmission, the CCA announced an immediate 'lockdown' starting from midnight on 25 March, comprising wide-ranging restrictions on freedom of movement, enforceable in law, whereby people have been ordered to stay at home and 'non-essential' businesses have been ordered to close. Several further emergency regulations have been enacted by the CCA to address the various challenges presented by the pandemic.\n\nThe pandemic has led to socio-economic disruption, the [[List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|cancellation or postponement of sporting and cultural events]], the [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education|closure of schools and colleges]] except for vulnerable children and children of critical workers, restrictions on travel (both within and to and from the Bailiwick), and fears of supply shortages have resulted in [[panic buying]]. The disruption to local business activities has resulted in closures and redundancies, though several schemes have been implemented by local banks and the States of Guernsey to provide financial support to businesses and individuals in order to limit the damage caused to the local economy.<ref name=\"loan scheme\"/><ref name=\"financial support schemes\"/>\n\nTesting was initially conducted by specialist laboratories in the UK, with no facilities available in the Bailiwick.<ref name=\"delayedresults\"/> Following rapid development, Guernsey's own testing facility became operational on 30 March, delivering results within 24 hours and prompting the adoption of a broader community testing programme.<ref name=\"on island testing\"/> As of 12 April, 1,719 samples have been tested, yielding 218 positive results and 1,421 negative results with 80 results yet to be confirmed. 48 patients have recovered.<ref name=\"test results\"/>\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nA new coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2) was first identified in Wuhan, Hubei, China, in late December 2019 as the cause of a cluster of cases of an acute respiratory disease now referred to as coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/china/news/detail/09-01-2020-who-statement-regarding-cluster-of-pneumonia-cases-in-wuhan-china |title=WHO Statement Regarding Cluster of Pneumonia Cases in Wuhan, China |publisher=WHO |date=31 December 2019 |accessdate=12 March 2020 }}</ref> As of March 2020 more than 170 countries and territories have been affected, with major outbreaks in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]].<ref name=\"WOM\">{{cite web |url= https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus Update (Live) |work=Worldometer |year=2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by Johns Hopkins CSSE|last=|first=|date=|website=gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> On March 11, 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) characterised the spread of COVID-19 as a [[pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 - 11 March 2020 |publisher=WHO |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51839944|title=Coronavirus confirmed as pandemic|date=2020-03-11|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline of cases==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Bailiwick of Guernsey medical cases chart}}\n===February===\n* On 23 February, it was reported that 12 local patients had been tested for the coronavirus with all results returning negative.<ref>{{cite news |title=All 12 Guernsey tests for Coronavirus return negative results |url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-02-23/all-12-guernsey-tests-for-coronavirus-return-negative-results/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=itv.com |agency=ITV |publisher=ITV News |date=23 February 2020}}</ref> \n* On 25 February, a group of children at a local school were sent home to self-isolate after returning from a ski trip to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|northern Italy]]; one symptomatic student was tested but the result came back negative.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus - Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) |url=https://www.gov.gg/coronavirus |website=gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306155752/https://www.gov.gg/coronavirus |accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-date=6 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Grammar School Ski Trip - Piedmont February 2020 |url=https://gov.gg/article/176458/Grammar-School-Ski-Trip---Piedmont-February-2020 |website=gov.gg |date=25 February 2020 |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* On 9 March, the first confirmed case was identified. The person had contracted the virus on holiday in Tenerife before returning home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jerseyeveningpost.com/news/2020/03/09/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-channel-islands/|title=First case of coronavirus confirmed in Channel Islands|last=Maguire|first=Jack|website=www.jerseyeveningpost.com|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> The patient sought help promptly, and their family was placed in compulsory quarantine at home.<ref name=\"firstcase\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Guernsey has first confirmed case |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-51801804 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=9 March 2020}}</ref> \n* On 12 March, Chief Minister Gavin St Pier described the pandemic as \"the most significant public health challenge since the end of the second world war\".<ref name=\"BBC News\"/> \n* On 20 March, a second case of coronavirus was confirmed in Guernsey\u2014eleven days after the first. The patient had returned from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]] before immediately entering a compulsory 14-day period of self-isolation during when they became symptomatic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mann |first1=Nick |title=Second coronavirus case confirmed |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/20/second-coronavirus-case-confirmed/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pouteaux |first1=Juliet |title=Second Covid-19 patient 'is doing extremely well' |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/20/second-covid-19-patient-is-doing-extremely-well/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 21 March, fifteen new cases were confirmed in the space of 24 hours, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 17. All cases were considered imported cases, each with a clear documented travel history, meaning no evidence of transmission within the Bailiwick.<ref name=\"21marchnewcases\">{{cite news |last1=Bowditch |first1=Helen |title=Coronavirus: 15 new cases confirmed in Guernsey |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/21/coronavirus-15-new-cases-confirmed-in-guernsey/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Each of the fifteen new patients suffered the relevant symptoms on their return and self-isolated as soon as they became symptomatic.<ref name=\"delayedresults\"/> \n* On 22 March, three further cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 20. The cases were also determined to be imported cases and not transmitted locally. In addition, the States of Guernsey identified four clusters among ten cases; three groups were on separate ski trips to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]] and one group was on a ski trip in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Austria|Austria]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany|Germany]]. It was also announced that around 1000 people were in compulsory self-isolation, about 1.5% of the local population.<ref name=\"test results\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowditch |first1=Helen |title=20 confirmed cases of Covid-19 now in island |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/22/20-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-now-in-island/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 23 March, no new cases were confirmed, and the States of Guernsey reaffirmed that a lockdown in the Bailiwick was not yet appropriate, warning of the likely economic and psychological consequences of such measures, and repeated the request for people to observe social distancing measures and practice good hygiene.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Coffell |first1=Zach |title='Trust us, we have got this, we'll get through it' |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/24/trust-us-we-have-got-this-well-get-through-it/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 24 March, three more cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 23; one of the three cases was confirmed to have been transmitted within the Bailiwick. At 7pm, the States of Guernsey announced in a live broadcast that a 'lockdown' period would begin from 00:01 on 25 March for two weeks during which restrictions would be placed on people's freedom of movement, enforceable by law.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |title='Strict' lockdown measures from midnight |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7a5199276ca90663acc23d%26%27Strict%27%20lockdown%20measures%20from%20midnight%262020-03-24T19%3A00%3A54.329Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:b2bb241b-8081-4dda-906a-73efd8e36889&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7a5199276ca90663acc23d&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Three measures to cut coronavirus s\">{{cite news |title=Three measures to cut coronavirus spread start at midnight |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7a561f30e3eb065b48e43b%26Three%20measures%20to%20cut%20coronavirus%20spread%20start%20at%20midnight%262020-03-24T19%3A06%3A29.826Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:0cbb69e2-f4af-45a4-a4d7-841e35b0b966&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7a561f30e3eb065b48e43b&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Restrictions are enforceable in la\">{{cite news |title=Restrictions are \"enforceable in law\" - Hardy |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7a67799103f706576ce74c%26Restrictions%20are%20%22enforceable%20in%20law%22%20-%20Hardy%262020-03-24T20%3A09%3A26.970Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:eee9c8c0-8ab7-490d-b721-0cbefd5ac505&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7a67799103f706576ce74c&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 25 March, seven new cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 30. Public Health also confirmed that it had tested 31 hospital in-patients suffering respiratory symptoms with all returning negative.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Seven more cases confirmed to bring total to 30 |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/25/coronavirus-seven-more-cases-confirmed-to-bring-total-to-30/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 26 March, four further cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 34; three of which were identified as locally transmitted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Four more cases in Guernsey brings island total to 34 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7ce01814627d0657f824ab%26Four%20more%20cases%20in%20Guernsey%20brings%20island%20total%20to%2034%262020-03-26T17%3A02%3A17.677Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:a8850906-c923-4105-bb59-1b937e903955&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7ce01814627d0657f824ab&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, the first death as a result of the coronavirus in the Channel Islands was confirmed after a patient died in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Jersey|Jersey]]. The patient was in their 80s and had underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitch |first1=Zoe |title=First coronavirus death in Channel Islands confirmed |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/26/first-coronavirus-death-in-channel-islands-confirmed/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 27 March, two more cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 36. It was also reported that one individual who did not self-isolate, despite showing symptoms, had tested positive and generated 73 contacts requiring tracing (compared to the average of around 20). 1,439 islanders were estimated to be in compulsory self-islation; around 2.2% of the island's population.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowditch |first1=Helen |title=Health tracing 73 contacts from single Covid-19 patient |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/27/health-tracing-73-contacts-from-single-covid-19-patient/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The hospital completed the conversion of its Day Care Unit into an [[Intensive Care Unit]] (ICU), ready to accommodate new COVID-19 patients.<ref name=\"icu\"/>\n* On 28 March, three more cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 39.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowditch |first1=Helen |title=Three people with coronavirus being treated in hospital |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/28/three-people-with-coronavirus-being-treated-in-hospital/ |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 29 March, six further cases were confirmed, bringing the total to 45. The Channel Islands also saw its second death from COVID-19 as a patient in their 70s died in Jersey.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowditch |first1=Helen |title=Second coronavirus death in Jersey |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/29/second-coronavirus-death-in-jersey/ |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 30 March, testing began in the Bailiwick of Guernsey, allowing results to be returned in less than 24 hours. Fifteen new cases were confirmed, including three care home residents, bringing the total number of cases to 60.<ref name=\"on island testing\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus testing: Guernsey on-island facility in use |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-52093933 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 31 March, the first COVID-19 related death in the Bailiwick was confirmed; the patient was 80 years old and passed away in the afternoon on the day prior.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: First death reported in Guernsey |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-52102681 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Eighteen more cases were confirmed\u2014the most in a day so far\u2014bringing the total cases to 78. Guernsey's [[Lieutenant Governor of Guernsey|Lieutenant Governor]], [[Vice admiral (Royal Navy)|Vice Admiral]] [[Ian Corder]], addressed the island at 16:00 and praised the 'discipline and stoicism' of islanders.<ref>{{cite news |title=Praise for Guernsey's 'discipline and stoicism' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e835e616d8c9806657fed83%26Praise%20for%20Guernsey%27s%20%27discipline%20and%20stoicism%27%262020-03-31T15%3A20%3A48.034Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:0359f3ab-f453-45bd-8a54-66e9909f7ced&pinned_post_asset_id=5e835e616d8c9806657fed83&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lieutenant Governor to address islanders at 16:00 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e834a7e6d8c9806657fed67%26Lieutenant%20Governor%20to%20address%20islanders%20at%2016%3A00%262020-03-31T13%3A49%3A51.630Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:af720682-ff13-46af-9d90-719f4d3f2385&pinned_post_asset_id=5e834a7e6d8c9806657fed67&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n* On 1 April, the number of cases reach a total of 91, up thirteen from the day before\u2014several of which were further cases at the care home where three cases had previously been identified.<ref>{{cite news |title=Number of Guernsey coronavirus cases up by 13 to 91 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e848601b03d0d066ff96122%26Number%20of%20Guernsey%20coronavirus%20cases%20up%20by%2013%20to%2091%262020-04-01T12%3A16%3A02.633Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:71c49f7d-483c-4103-9cd4-d5f993de7c32&pinned_post_asset_id=5e848601b03d0d066ff96122&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus affected care home in 'difficult position' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e848b00b03d0d066ff9612e%26Coronavirus%20affected%20care%20home%20in%20%27difficult%20position%27%262020-04-01T12%3A39%3A09.311Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:c1451cbe-01c1-4b0e-8697-0dcb20dbbf70&pinned_post_asset_id=5e848b00b03d0d066ff9612e&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> A delivery of personal protection equipment (PPE) arrived and is being 'controlled carefully' due to global shortages of such equipment.<ref name=\"delayphase\">{{cite news |last1=Bowditch |first1=Helen |title=WATCH: Coronavirus: 91 confirmed cases |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/01/watch-coronavirus-91-confirmed-cases-27-in-care-home/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n* On 2 April, six more cases were confirmed, bringing the total cases to 97.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guernsey coronavirus cases up by six to 97 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e8607024f63c606765ce29e%26Guernsey%20coronavirus%20cases%20up%20by%20six%20to%2097%262020-04-02T15%3A38%3A44.051Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:6051d631-6674-422a-a93f-5fa0bb6e39b4&pinned_post_asset_id=5e8607024f63c606765ce29e&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> A marine ambulance was sent to Sark in the early hours of the morning\u2014the second in 24 hours\u2014and a patient was taken to the Princess Elizabeth Hospital.<ref>{{cite news |title=Second marine ambulance call to Sark in 24 hours |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e85f14f3b6ca8066df6e511%26Second%20marine%20ambulance%20call%20to%20Sark%20in%2024%20hours%262020-04-02T14%3A06%3A08.946Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:60105f96-1ed4-4c62-a1b7-0a6bd96a2c4d&pinned_post_asset_id=5e85f14f3b6ca8066df6e511&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* On 3 April, it was announced that a second patient had died from the disease. Seventeen more cases were confirmed, bringing the total number to 114. It was also announced that a second care home cluster had been identified.<ref name=\"3aprilgp\">{{cite news |last1=Fitch |first1=Zoe |title=Second Covid-19 death and another cluster found |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/03/second-covid-19-death-and-another-cluster-found/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> The number of recoveries was reported for the first time that day, at 13.<ref name=\"test results\"/>\n* On 4 April, twenty-two cases were identified along with two further recoveries, totalling 136 confirmed cases and 15 recoveries.<ref name=\"test results\"/>\n* On 5 April, a third death was announced. Like the first two deaths, the person was over the age of 80.<ref>{{cite news |title=Third person dies from Covid-19 in Guernsey |url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-04-05/third-person-dies-from-covid-19-in-guernsey/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=itv.com |agency=ITV |publisher=ITV News |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> The number of tests taken passed 1,000 as twelve more recoveries and eighteen more confirmed cases were reported, for a total of 27 recoveries from 154 confirmed cases.<ref name=\"test results\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Recovered up to 27 as total cases rises above 150 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52149479?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e8ad348cfdb750670d9c1f0%26Recovered%20up%20to%2027%20as%20total%20cases%20rises%20above%20150%262020-04-06T07%3A01%3A39.681Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:4981ec69-c451-459d-b6a9-440cf2d023e1&pinned_post_asset_id=5e8ad348cfdb750670d9c1f0&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n* On 6 April, a fourth death was announced; all four were in their 80s. Another recovery and eleven new cases were confirmed, totalling 165 confirmed cases and 28 recoveries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clayton |first1=Laura |title=Fourth death announced |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/fourth-death-announced/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n* On 7 April, the lockdown period was extended for another two weeks. One more case was confirmed as well as six more recoveries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenneally |first1=Danielle |title=WATCH: 'Staying at home is the best way to save lives' |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/07/watch-staying-at-home-is-the-best-way-to-save-lives/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* On 8 April, the number of confirmed cases rose by fifteen to 181, with 38 recoveries. Seven total deaths have been recorded (5 confirmed due to COVID-19 and 2 presumed).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitch |first1=Zoe |title=Five confirmed Covid-19 deaths and two more presumed to be linked |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/08/five-confirmed-covid-19-deaths-and-two-more-presumed-to-be-linked/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n* On 10 April, a sixth confirmed death due to COVID-19 was announced, along with 9 new cases and 2 recoveries, totalling 200 confirmed cases with 42 recoveries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenneally |first1=Danielle |title=Sixth Covid-19 death confirmed |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/10/please-write-your-example-heading-here/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Response by the States of Guernsey==\n===Strategy and administration===\nIn accordance with [[World Health Organisation]] (WHO) guidelines for managing a pandemic, the States of Guernsey response strategy has been designed specifically for the Bailiwick and continues to adapt in line with changing numbers of cases and developing situations in other jurisdictions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clayton |first1=Laura |title=17 cases confirmed |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/17-cases-confirmed/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> The underlying principle of the States of Guernsey's strategy to deal with the pandemic, as explained by Dr Nicola Brink, the Director for Public Health, is to \"[[flatten the curve]]\", which refers to decreasing the peak of the [[epidemic curve]] through a number of measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clayton |first1=Laura |title=WATCH: We're trying to \"flatten the curve\" |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/were-trying-flatten-curve/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> This slowing of the rate of infection decreases the risk of health services being overwhelmed, allows for the better treatment of current cases, and delays additional cases until a vaccine become available.<ref name=\"Lancet2020Flatten\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Anderson RM, Heesterbeek H, Klinkenberg D, Hollingsworth TD | title = How will country-based mitigation measures influence the course of the COVID-19 epidemic? | journal = Lancet | date = March 2020 | volume = 395 | issue = 10228 | pages = 931\u2013934 | pmid = 32164834 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30567-5 | quote = A key issue for epidemiologists is helping policy makers decide the main objectives of mitigation\u2014e.g. minimising morbidity and associated mortality, avoiding an epidemic peak that overwhelms health-care services, keeping the effects on the economy within manageable levels, and flattening the epidemic curve to wait for vaccine development and manufacture on scale and antiviral drug therapies. | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nThe response is led by the Civil Contingencies Authority (CCA), a body made up of several committee Presidents and chaired by the head of the Policy and Resources Committee (P&R)\u2014the island's senior politician\u2014Gavin St Pier. The body is responsible for coordinating actions in circumstances \"that present a serious risk to the health and welfare of Island residents\". The CCA is advised by the Policy and Resources Committee (the States of Guernsey's senior committee), the Committee for Health and Social Care (HSC), and Public Health Services (overseen by HSC). The Coronavirus Political Executive Group was also established to include political representation from all principal States committees to make decisions on matters which do not engage the CCA.<ref>{{cite web |title=Civil Contingencies Authority meets as coronavirus situation continues to develop |url=https://gov.gg/article/176791/Civil-Contingencies-Authority-meets-as-coronavirus-situation-continues-to-develop |website=gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 30 March, St Pier revealed that the States were considering temporary changes to its system of government following concerns over a lack of scrutiny of decisions being made by the CCA\u2014a body designed for \"short-term emergencies\"\u2014due to the [[States of Guernsey|States of Deliberation]] not sitting as normal.<ref>{{cite news |title=States looking to 'temporarily amend' system of government |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e81ef9b4e049e066f59621b%26States%20looking%20to%20%27temporarily%20amend%27%20system%20of%20government%262020-03-30T13%3A30%3A33.237Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:6ed5b971-168a-4ddb-97b2-b5892d35b3a7&pinned_post_asset_id=5e81ef9b4e049e066f59621b&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe States of Guernsey first acknlowedged the emergence of a novel coronavirus, referred to as 2019-nCoV Novel Coronavirus (Wuhan Virus), on 23 January when there were 571 known cases of infection worldwide. In November 2019, the States had successfully conducted an exercise of the Channel Islands Strategic Pandemic Influenza Plan, a simulation flu pandemic exercise led by Public Health Services. The simulation exercise was promted by pandemic outbreak being moved to the top of the island's risk register following public health advice from the WHO. The States asserted in a media statement on 23 January that they were \"in a good position to respond to the developing 2019-nCoV situation\" and advised individuals to seek medical help immediately if they develop respiratory symptoms after returning from Wuhan to the island.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media release - Wuhan novel coronavirus |url=https://covid19.gov.gg/sites/default/files/2020-04/Media%20release%20-%2023%20January%202020%20-%20Wuhan%20novel%20coronavirus%20%5B531kb%5D.pdf |website=covid19.gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=6 April 2020 |date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Carpenter |first1=Aaron |title=Invaluable lessons were learned |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/invaluable-lessons-were-learned/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===History of response===\n====6 February\u201324 March: Early measures and containment phase====\n[[File:States_of_Guernsey_coronavirus_public_info_poster.pdf|thumb|upright=0.9|right|States of Guernsey self-isolation advice poster, March 2020<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Coronavirus - Resources, News & Statements |url=https://www.gov.gg/covid19resources |website=gov.gg |date=10 March 2020 |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>]]\nOn 6 February, the States of Guernsey published information advising islanders returning from Mainland China to self-isolate for 14 days upon their arrival in the Bailiwick \"to reduce the risk of the infection being introduced to the island\u2019s community\", referencing [[Public Health England]]'s self-isolation guidelines to not attend work, school or public places, to avoid visitors in your home, and to avoid using public transport or taxis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media release - Self-Isolation |url=https://covid19.gov.gg/sites/default/files/2020-04/Media%20release%20-%206%20February%202020%20-%20self-isolation%20%5B445kb%5D.pdf |website=covid19.gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=6 April 2020 |date=6 February 2020}}</ref> A day later, the States expanded the list of 'affected areas' from which return requires self-isolation to include Mainland China, Hong Kong, Japan, Macau, Malaysia, the Republic of South Korea, Singapore, Taiwan, and Thailand.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media release - Novel Coronavirus 2019-nCoV Updated advice for travellers returning from an affected area |url=https://covid19.gov.gg/sites/default/files/2020-04/Media%20release%20-%207%20February%202020%20-%20updated%20advice%20for%20travellers%20returning%20from%20an%20affected%20area%20%5B435kb%5D.pdf |website=covid19.gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=6 April 2020 |date=7 February 2020}}</ref> On 10 February, the States of Guernsey confirmed that seven local residents had been tested for the novel coronavirus, though asked that islanders \"avoid speculation or worry\".<ref name=\"10feb\"/> On 25 February, the States of Guernsey updated their self-islation information for returning residents, defining Group A and Group B areas. Residents returning from Group A areas (Mainland China, Iran, South Korea and some parts of Italy) were required to self-isolate for 14 days upon arrival, while those returning from Group B areas were required to self-isolate only if they had symptoms.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media release - Public Health Services releases further information on self-isolation |url=https://covid19.gov.gg/sites/default/files/2020-04/Media%20release%20-%2025%20February%202020%20-%20updated%20self-isolation%20advice%20%5B465kb%5D.pdf |website=covid19.gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=6 April 2020 |date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly advice given to the public by the States of Guernsey, forming the foundations of the 'containment' phase of the response consisted of [[behaviour change (public health)|behaviour changing]] publicity encouraging hand-washing for at least twenty seconds, avoiding touching your own face, and practising respiratory hygiene as well as advising social distancing and keeping at least {{Convert|2|m|ft|1}} from others, especially those showing symptoms.<ref name=\"selfislationadvice\"/><ref name=\"10feb\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Update |url=https://covid19.gov.gg/sites/default/files/2020-04/Media%20release%20-%2010%20February%202020%20-%20coronavirus%20update%20%5B447kb%5D.pdf |website=covid19.gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=6 April 2020 |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> The States of Guernsey also published advice on supporting others in the community, encouraging the public to telephone elderly or vulnerable family members, friends and neighbours, offer to shop for those in self-isolation and to avoid non-essential off-island travel.<ref name=\"selfislationadvice\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Advice |url=https://www.gov.gg/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=124021&p=0 |website=gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey}}</ref> The Health Improvement Commission also published advice and resources with guidance on exercises to keep families healthy and active during self-isolation, recommending two 20- to 30-minute sessions per day to maintain physical and mental wellbeing. They also clarified that while individuals may go outside to exercise alone while social distancing, they should stay at home where possible.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exercise resources during social distancing |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e78d1692940ec06703e13c7%26Exercise%20resources%20during%20social%20distancing%262020-03-23T15%3A26%3A53.870Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:226f8a6f-7c06-4624-a26b-81629ef97736&pinned_post_asset_id=5e78d1692940ec06703e13c7&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:SoG coronavirus message.png|thumb|The States of Guernsey utilised technology to send mass SMS messages for the first time to provide regular updates on their response to the pandemic.]]\nThe first case in the Bailiwick was confirmed on 9 March, after which the CCA enacted the Emergency Powers (Coronavirus) (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Regulations 2020, coming into effect on 18 March: the first of a number of emergency powers regulations introduced in the States of Guernsey's response to the pandemic. The statutory instrument enables the Medical Officer of Health to implement emergency measures enforceable by law, the first of which mandated that anyone arriving in the Bailiwick from anywhere self-isolate for 14 days upon arrival from midnight on 19 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Coronavirus - Latest information and testing results |url=https://gov.gg/coronavirus |website=gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Anyone travelling to Guernsey must self-isolate |url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-17/anyone-travelling-to-guernsey-has-to-self-isolate/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=itv.com |agency=ITV |publisher=ITV News |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The regulations also grant law enforcement officers detain individuals whom they suspect may have the coronavirus and present a risk of spreading it to others until the Medical Officer of Health can advise further.<ref name=\"1702mediarelease\"/> On 18 March the States utilised for the first time the databases of [[Sure (company)|Sure]], [[JT Group Limited|JT]] and [[Airtel-Vodafone]] to send a mass SMS message with information about self-isolation to numbers used in the Bailiwick. The technology is reserved for critical emergencies or public health threats.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clayton |first1=Laura |title=Telcos help States share message |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/telcos-help-states-share-message/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====25 March\u20136 April: Lockdown and transition to delay phase====\n[[File:States_of_Guernsey_Coronavirus_Stay_at_Home.pdf|thumb|upright=0.9|right|Leaflets were sent to every household in the Bailiwick setting out the strict lockdown measures imposed from 25 March.]]\nFollowing the confirmation of a case resulting from on-island transmission on 24 March, the States of Guernsey announced in a live broadcast that it was implementing a 'lockdown' for an initial period of two weeks from 00:01 on 25 March, whereby restrictions would be placed on people's freedom of movement, enforceable under the statutory instrument, the Emergency Powers (Coronavirus) (Control of Events, Gatherings and Meetings) (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Regulations, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Emergency Powers (Coronavirus) (Control of Events, Gatherings and Meetings) (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Regulations, 2020 |url=http://www.guernseylegalresources.gg/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=124199&p=0 |website=guernseylegalresources.gg |publisher=Guernsey Legal Resources |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"Three measures to cut coronavirus s\"/><ref name=\"Restrictions are enforceable in la\"/> \n\nThe measures require people to stay at home except for shopping for basic necessities, medical requirements, two hours of exercise per day, and travelling to and from work for 'essential' jobs which 'absolutely cannot be done from home'. Other measures include the closure of all non-essential shops, businesses and community spaces, and the banning of public gatherings of more than two people (excluding people from the same household).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clayton |first1=Laura |title=BREAKING: We're in 'lockdown' |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/breaking-stay-inside/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Weddings, baptisms and other religious ceremonies were also banned, while funerals would continue but with only immediate family permitted to attend.<ref>{{cite news |title=Public gatherings of more than two banned |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7a5b9730e3eb065b48e440%26Public%20gatherings%20of%20more%20than%20two%20banned%262020-03-24T19%3A28%3A33.783Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:1e23e92d-14a7-4f96-8b4e-6accbd9e7169&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7a5b9730e3eb065b48e440&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Gavin St Pier drew comparisons with the restrictions to those imposed during [[German occupation of the Channel Islands|the occupation of the Channel Islands during world war two]], commenting \"These measures introduce the most far reaching deprivation of personal liberties since the second world war\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Strict new measures come into force from midnight tonight |url=https://www.gov.gg/covid19newmeasures |website=gov.gg |date=24 March 2020 |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On 29 March, the States of Guernsey issued detailed revisions to the lockdown measures for businesses and the self-employed following some confusion over which sectors were still able to work.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Green |first1=Will |title=Apology over business lockdown guidance as financial help for firms and self-employed on the way |url=https://guernseypress.com/top-stories/homepage/2020/03/29/apology-over-business-lockdown-guidance-as-financial-help-for-firms-and-self-employed-on-the-way-2/ |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the States of Guernsey announced 'shielding' measures for extremely vulnerable individuals, advising them to stay at home for 12 weeks and minimise all physical contact with others.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carpenter |first1=Aaron |title=High risk individuals asked to stay home for 12 weeks |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/shielding-those-who-are-extremely-vulnerable/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> With the number of cases reaching 91 on 1 April, the response was reported to be moving to the 'delay' phase of the strategy.<ref name=\"delayphase\"/> The States of Guernsey also clarified that leaving the house to escape domestic abuse was acceptable as it would be considered an essential reason, and published guidance for victims of domestic abuse and recommended an app which allows the user's smartphone to become a safety device, sending their location to designated contacts when activated by shaking the phone.<ref>{{cite web |title=Domestic Abuse - physical, emotional, financial, sexual or psychological |url=https://www.gov.gg/coronavirus |website=gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> St Pier also appealed for islanders to complete a voluntary online form in order to gather information on \"how the community are feeling\", and asked islanders to send questions to the States via email to be answered at the next press conference.<ref>{{cite news |title=Islanders asked to send Covid-19 questions to the States |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e84992a78a0e10663a116d7%26Islanders%20asked%20to%20send%20Covid-19%20questions%20to%20the%20States%262020-04-01T13%3A58%3A30.550Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:6a050ce0-bf0d-4c7e-817c-1a15a3d3353a&pinned_post_asset_id=5e84992a78a0e10663a116d7&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Community Monitoring Tool now available - 1st April 2020 |url=https://www.gov.gg/coronavirus |website=gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, the CCA approved the following statutory emergency regulations, described by St Pier as being \"largely designed to plan ahead to enable us to better manage issues that will emerge as a result of the need for us to all keep our distance from each other\", all of which came into effect the same day:\n* The Emergency Powers (Coronavirus) (Mental Health) (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Regulations, 2020, which modifies certain requirements stipulated in the Mental Health (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Law 2010 per advice by the HSC following concerns over its functioning during the pandemic.\n* The Emergency Powers (Coronavirus) (Parochial Matters and Miscellaneous Provisions) (Guernsey) Regulations, 2020, which enables parishes to continue conducting business in the absence of ratepayers\u2019 meetings which are now impossible under lockdown restrictions.\n* The Emergency Powers (Coronavirus) (Registration of Deaths etc. and Cremation Procedures) (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Regulations, 2020, which modifies procedures in relation to deaths and cremations to prevent the spread of COVID-19.\n* The Emergency Powers (Coronavirus) (Temporary Registration of Health Professionals) (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Regulations, 2020, which allows HSC to temporarily hire retired or non-practising medical professionals (who would ordinarily be required to be registered in the UK) should they consider it necessary and proportionate to do so.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 information and documentation |url=http://www.guernseylawofficers.gg/article/176933/COVID-19-information-and-documentation |website=guernseylawofficers.gg |date=25 March 2020 |publisher=Law Officers of the Crown |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Emergency Powers (Coronavirus) (Registration of Deaths etc. and Cremation Procedures) (Bailiwick of Guernsey) Regulations, 2020 |url=http://www.guernseylegalresources.gg/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=124377&p=0 |website=www.guernseylegalresources.gg/ |publisher=Guernsey Legal Resources |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release - Civil Contingencies Authority regulations |url=https://covid19.gov.gg/sites/default/files/2020-04/Media%20release%20-%206%20April%202020%20-%20Civil%20Contingencies%20Authority%20regulations%20%5B538kb%5D.pdf |website=covid19.gov.gg/ |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, the Overseas Aid and Development Commission (OA&DC) (constituted as a committee of the States of Guernsey) agreed to suspend all grants anticipated for projects in 2021 in order to save and return over \u00a31 million to the States of Guernsey to support the response to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitch |first1=Zoe |title=\u00a31m. of unspent overseas aid returned to help local coronavirus response |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/05/1m-of-unspent-overseas-aid-returned-to-help-local-coronavirus-response/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> Following confirmation of two clusters of cases in separate care homes in Guernsey with tens of staff and residents being diagnosed with COVID-19, the States of Guernsey published an 'urgent public request' for former care home workers or volunteers to help out in care homes and community care facilities, as well as designating a separate programme designed specifically for responding to the pandemic within the care home sector in the Bailiwick.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carpenter |first1=Aaron |title=Care homes being \"individually assessed\" |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/care-homes-being-individually-assessed/#.XooTwi2ZNQI |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Clayton |first1=Laura |title=Help needed in the care homes |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/help-needed-care-homes/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====7 April\u2013present: Lockdown extended====\nOn 7 April, the States of Guernsey confirmed in a live media briefing that the lockdown measures would remain in place for at least another 14 days. Changes were made to restrictions on businesses, taking effect from midnight on 8 April, to allow non-essential retailers to carry out home deliveries, providing strict social distancing and hygiene measures are followed and no more than two employees are on the premises.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitch |first1=Zoe |title=Lockdown continues under review |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/07/lockdown-continues-under-review/ |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title='Lock down' restrictions for Islanders to stay at home continue |url=https://covid19.gov.gg/sites/default/files/2020-04/Media%20release%20-%207%20April%202020%20-%20Lock%20down%20restrictions%20to%20continue%20%5B548kb%5D.pdf |website=covid19.gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Recognising the high proportion of deaths and cases coming from care homes across the island, the States of Guernsey decided on 9 April to stop all care home visits by family and friends \"for the foreseeable future\". All hospital visits to COVID-19 wards or patients are not permitted, and hospices will stop routine visits; 'end of life' visits will be assessed individually.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitch |first1=Zoe |title=All care home and hospital visits must stop |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/09/all-care-home-and-hospital-visits-must-stop/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare and treatment===\nThe Committee for Health and Social Care announced, on 19 March, its plans for the island's only hospital\u2014the Princess Elizabeth Hospital (PEH)\u2014to respond to the development of the spread of COVID-19 on the island. Measures taken include the suspension of elective surgery from 23 March, training staff to \"increase resilience in the provision of critical care\", and limiting in-patients to one visitor at a time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health service planning for potential spread of virus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51943602?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7330554f54d906677987bc%26Health%20service%20planning%20for%20potential%20spread%20of%20virus%262020-03-19T09%3A32%3A37.617Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:df2ea29d-737a-4c6f-84d0-987bcb62a55c&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7330554f54d906677987bc&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March the States of Guernsey made the decision to close the hospital to visitors with exceptions for people in end of life care and occupants of the maternity and children's wards.<ref>{{cite news |title=Princess Elizabeth Hospital closed to visitors |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7898332940ec06703e1358%26Princess%20Elizabeth%20Hospital%20closed%20to%20visitors%262020-03-23T11%3A09%3A26.884Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:e0e3641f-5c75-47bc-8f91-475c64f96bcd&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7898332940ec06703e1358&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> In order to combat the pandemic, [[Nursing agency|agency nurses]] due to return to the UK stayed in Guernsey to work the hospital.<ref name=\"agencynurses\">{{cite news |title=Agency nurses remain at Princess Elizabeth Hospital |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e819c479103f706576cef01%26Agency%20nurses%20remain%20at%20Princess%20Elizabeth%20Hospital%262020-03-30T08%3A03%3A31.682Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:568ddf33-3f2c-4f9f-97b6-91ecefa9f40b&pinned_post_asset_id=5e819c479103f706576cef01&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC Radio Guernsey |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, the hospital's Day Care Unit completed its two-week conversion into an [[Intensive Care Unit]] (ICU) in preparation for accommodation potential coronavirus patients. It was also reported that Guernsey \"started with more intensive care beds than the UK per head of population\" and was \"already in a good position for ventilators\".<ref name=\"icu\">{{cite news |title=Day Unit converted to Intensive Care Unit |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7ddc8b9103f706576ceb22%26Day%20Unit%20converted%20to%20Intensive%20Care%20Unit%262020-03-27T10%3A59%3A25.550Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:204fbc68-4ed5-4132-92b9-2b72ecba1743&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7ddc8b9103f706576ceb22&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, the hospital adopted a new streaming system, whereby patients entering the Emergency Department must first meet with a streaming nurse who will question the patient about their travel history, self-isolation and possible contact with COVID-19-positive patients. Once assessed, the patient is sent to either Red Zone 1 if they have COVID-19 symptoms or have had contact with a positive patient, or to Yellow Zone 2 if they are symptom free.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: New system introduced at Guernsey's Emergency Department |url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-27/coronavirus-new-system-introduced-at-guernsey-s-emergency-department/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=itv.com |agency=ITV |publisher=ITV News |date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Foote |first1=Maisie |title=WATCH: More change at the PEH |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/watch-more-change-peh/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> All nurses and staff in the dedicated unit are required to wear protective equipment.<ref name=\"agencynurses\"/>\n\nOn 30 March, the Medical Director of Health and Social Care, Dr Peter Rabey, gave assurances that the Princess Elizabeth Hospital was \"well prepared\" for an increase in patients suffering from COVID-19 and said that Guernsey has more ventilators per head of population than the UK.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guernsey has 'more ventilators per person than UK' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e81e6181683fd0681c179c7%26Guernsey%20has%20%27more%20ventilators%20per%20person%20than%20UK%27%262020-03-30T12%3A30%3A59.468Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:4ed0d4ab-b5be-42c1-ad12-c023d336898e&pinned_post_asset_id=5e81e6181683fd0681c179c7&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hospital 'well prepared' for growth in patients |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e81ef9c14627d0657f82a59%26Hospital%20%27well%20prepared%27%20for%20growth%20in%20patients%262020-03-30T13%3A15%3A21.283Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:7a0c801f-85e9-4db3-aa4f-c1d891d404f4&pinned_post_asset_id=5e81ef9c14627d0657f82a59&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> On 31 March, it was announced that patients going to the hospital presenting symptoms related to COVID-19 would not have to pay for a check-up nor pay for their treatment.<ref>{{cite news |title=No emergency charges for coronavirus symptoms |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e83682814627d0657f82c34%26No%20emergency%20charges%20for%20coronavirus%20symptoms%262020-03-31T16%3A07%3A24.623Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:399bbab0-2f57-4d97-8888-13d2f188a258&pinned_post_asset_id=5e83682814627d0657f82c34&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> On 2 April, it was announced that the Chest and Heart unit at the hospital would, from the next day, function as the designated doctors' surgery for anyone instructed to book an appointment after phoning their local surgery and presenting symptoms of an upper respiratory tract infection.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitch |first1=Zoe |title=Coronavirus: Chest and Heart unit new dedicated surgery for flu-like symptoms |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/02/coronavirus-chest-and-heart-unit-new-dedicated-surgery-for-flu-like-symptoms/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> On 5 April, it was announced that HSC would be spending between \u00a315 million and \u00a320 million to update the Princess Elizabeth Hospital's \"ageing and increasingly vulnerable\" health record system, expected to be installed over 18 months, to aid the response to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowditch |first1=Helen |title=Urgent need to update health's record system |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/04/05/urgent-need-to-update-healths-record-system/ |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 12 April, there are 9 patients with COVID-19 being treated at the Princess Elizabeth Hospital for COVID-19; none are currently in intensive care or require ventilatory support. The States of Guernsey have predicted that between 8\u201315% of all COVID-19 cases will require hospital care.<ref>{{cite web |title=Testing results - Hospital cases |url=https://covid19.gov.gg/test-results |website=gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Financial support measures===\nOn 19 March the States of Guernsey announced that it had made available a \u00a35 million 'hardship fund' for any islanders (excluding those already eligible to receive national social security benefits) struggling financially from the impact of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00a35 million hardship fund opens for Guernsey people |url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-19/5-million-hardship-fund-opens-for-guernsey-people/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=itv.com |agency=ITV |publisher=ITV News |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> The States also set up a government-funded health insurance scheme to cover the medical bills of any Bailiwick residents who fall ill while visiting the UK, providing they can prove they cannot afford private health insurance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carpenter |first1=Aaron |title=Corona caveat added to UK health insurance |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/corona-caveat-added-uk-health-insurance/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> The States also announced on 23 March that it would be amending population law to protect non-residents who might find themselves without employment as a result of the pandemic and would otherwise be forced to leave the island.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clayton |first1=Laura |title=Population law to change amid corona virus outbreak |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/population-law-change-amid-corona-virus-outbreak/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the States of Guernsey also published advice to businesses including a number of financial 'easements' such as deferrals on social insurance payments and commercial tax on real property, and rent reliefs on government-owned property.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus ('COVID 19') Business Support |url=https://www.gov.gg/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=124065&p=0 |website=gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, the finalised emergency financial measures were approved including \u00a330 million to support businesses, a \u00a340 million loan guarantee scheme for locally-trading firms and a \u00a325 million temporary overdraft for local airline [[Aurigny]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carpenter |first1=Aaron |title=Emergency financial measures approved |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/emergency-financial-measures-approved/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 24 March the [[Guernsey Financial Services Commission]] (GFSC) approved time extensions for businesses to file their financial returns in light of operational issues suffered as a result of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Businesses given more time to file financial returns |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7a088630e3eb065b48e3be%26Businesses%20given%20more%20time%20to%20file%20financial%20returns%262020-03-24T13%3A23%3A50.733Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:69d03873-58ed-4d6e-866e-518a16388c5d&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7a088630e3eb065b48e3be&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March the Policy and Resources Committee announced two new schemes to support businesses and the self-employed, with both schemes totalling an estimated \u00a341 million. The payroll co-sharing scheme\u2014lasting for an initial period of 13 weeks\u2014will cover 80% of employee wages, based on the Guernsey minimum wage of \u00a38.50 per hour (equating to \u00a3238 for a 35-hour week), with the remaining 20% expected to be covered by businesses themselves; there is no restriction placed on the size of the businesses eligible for this scheme. The grants scheme allows small businesses (of fewer than 10 people) and the self-employed to be awarded a \u00a33000 grant to be utilised in \"whichever way they deem appropriate\". The committee predicted that around 1,700 businesses will qualify for the scheme with roughly 10,500 total employees.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schemes costing \u00a341m to support business and self-employed |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7a14bc30e3eb065b48e3d5%26Schemes%20costing%20%C2%A341m%20to%20support%20business%20and%20self-employed%262020-03-24T14%3A24%3A13.974Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:cca00219-843a-4d11-bbc9-127ef052f4bb&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7a14bc30e3eb065b48e3d5&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"financial support schemes\">{{cite web |title=States to establish payroll co-sharing and grants to support businesses and the self-employed |url=https://gov.gg/article/176903/States-to-establish-payroll-co-sharing-and-grants-to-support-businesses-and-the-self-employed |website=gov.gg |date=24 March 2020 |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident of the Policy and Resources Committee, Gavin St Pier, confirmed on 27 March that local banks had been given flexibility by their regulator\u2014the [[Bank of England]]\u2014to give more loans to individuals and businesses and encouraged anyone in need to contact them and arrange a loan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Foote |first1=Maisie |title=Extra flexibility for bank loans |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/financial-support-businesses/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 30 March, a \u00a340m loan guarantee scheme was launched by the States of Guernsey in partnership with the governments of the other [[Crown Dependencies]] of [[Jersey]] and the [[Isle of Man]], and operated by [[Barclays]], [[HSBC]], [[Lloyds Bank|Lloyds]] and [[RBS International|RBSI and NatWest International]], to provide further support for businesses. The scheme enables businesses to take out new loans and overdrafts of up to \u00a3500,000, with 80% of the total amount provided to be underwritten by the States of Guernsey.<ref name=\"loan scheme\">{{cite news |title=States launches \u00a340m loan guarantee scheme |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e820b6e4e049e066f59623e%26States%20launches%20%C2%A340m%20loan%20guarantee%20scheme%262020-03-30T15%3A16%3A49.387Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:a4cda813-f21d-41ea-a433-ca84ac88df0c&pinned_post_asset_id=5e820b6e4e049e066f59623e&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n===Testing and surveillance===\n====Development of facilities====\nWithout testing facilities available locally, samples were initially sent off-island to be tested by a specialist laboratory in the UK until the Bailiwick had developed its own.<ref name=\"education\"/> Due to the increased demand on UK laboratories to conduct tests, the time taken for results to be received was significantly increased on several occasions beyond the standard time of 48 hours.<ref name=\"test results\"/><ref name=\"delayedresults\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Guernsey test results delayed by more than a week |url=https://www.itv.com/news/channel/2020-03-21/coronavirus-guernsey-test-results-delayed-by-more-than-a-week/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=itv.co.uk |agency=ITV |publisher=ITV News |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, the Policy and Resources Committee announced that it expected Guernsey to be carrying out tests by April and to deliver results within 24 hours.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus tests in Guernsey 'by April' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-guernsey-51987124 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=On-island test results 'on same day' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51943602?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e7394fe61880c065baef666%26On-island%20test%20results%20%27on%20same%20day%27%262020-03-19T16%3A05%3A50.402Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:831ea091-a10e-4567-bdc5-d2602c600b12&pinned_post_asset_id=5e7394fe61880c065baef666&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> In a letter sent to the [[Prime Minister of U.K.|UK's Prime Minister]], [[Boris Johnson]], on 20 March, Gavin St Pier explained how the UK testing centre initially testing Guernsey samples had discontinued their support and demanded a guarantee that testing support would be provided to the Crown Dependencies from the UK until Guernsey had established its own testing facility; the response from Johnson obliged, confirming that Colindale Public Health Laboratory would provide testing facilities until Guernsey could do so itself.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowditch |first1=Helen |title=PM promises testing support until island can do it itself |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/30/pm-promises-testing-support-until-island-can-do-it-itself/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the Director of Public Health confirmed that the island would have two ways of testing for the coronavirus, with results available in half a day, and that tests would be prioritised for healthcare workers, hospital patients with respiratory symptoms and islanders showing the relevant symptoms needing to see a doctor.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mann |first1=Nick |title=Test results in half a day once all the equipment arrives |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/25/test-results-in-half-a-day-once-all-the-equipment-arrives/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, it was announced that the final piece of equipment required for on-island testing had arrived and that testing would begin once staff were trained and due checks were completed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowditch |first1=Helen |title=Final piece of virus testing kit is here |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2020/03/26/final-piece-of-virus-testing-kit-is-here/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> On 30 March, it was announced that local testing facility was in use, meaning results would be available far quicker than tests conducted off-island. As a result, Public Health announced that from 31 March they will conduct a broader community testing programme, testing individuals suffering respiratory problems at local doctors' surgeries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guernsey to start 'broader' testing programme |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e81ea26a8854e067111a803%26Guernsey%20to%20start%20%27broader%27%20testing%20programme%262020-03-30T12%3A52%3A24.883Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:688dd524-9780-49b0-9f84-d7571b13978f&pinned_post_asset_id=5e81ea26a8854e067111a803&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"on island testing\"/> The States of Guernsey has described the testing process as 'quick and simple', saying that those unable to drive or be driven to the screening facility can make arrangements to be tested at home.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus testing: 'Quick and simple' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e810355988dc4066d32ef37%26Coronavirus%20testing%3A%20%27Quick%20and%20simple%27%262020-03-30T06%3A36%3A13.770Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:612edc63-6354-4e88-9b63-d0024ec03c76&pinned_post_asset_id=5e810355988dc4066d32ef37&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Surveillance of cases====\nDr Nicola Brink, the Director for Public Health, explained the process of dealing with suspected cases as follows: detection of a possible case; immediate [[Isolation (health care)#Self-isolation|quarantine]]; and [[contact tracing]], to identify those at risk of transmission from that possible case and test, monitor and isolate them to stop the spread of the disease.<ref>{{cite news |title=Public Health was 'expecting' rise in cases |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-51999470?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e78a0fd30e3eb065b48e1ff%26Public%20Health%20was%20%27expecting%27%20rise%20in%20cases%262020-03-23T11%3A47%3A04.892Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:392bcd05-0807-4b31-bf6f-b4513d6e12be&pinned_post_asset_id=5e78a0fd30e3eb065b48e1ff&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Those who have been contacted directly by the States of Guernsey and ordered to self-isolate (such as individuals with confirmed cases, contacts of confirmed cases and individuals booked for testing or awaiting results) are subject to regular welfare checks; the checks were originally conducted by Public Health Services before being taken over by [[Voluntary sector|third sector]] volunteers.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Coronavirus - Testing results - Daily Welfare Calls |url=https://www.gov.gg/covid19testresults |website=gov.gg |date=20 March 2020 |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, it was revealed that hospital workers are prioritised for testing should they display any of the relevant symptoms and that workers would be withdrawn from work if they are feeling even slightly unwell and rapidly tested. Dr Brink also announced that once antibody testing\u2014which can identify individuals immune to the disease\u2014becomes available, hospital workers would again be prioritised.<ref>{{cite news |title='Low threshold' to test Guernsey health workers |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e872febcfdb750670d9bdea%26%27Low%20threshold%27%20to%20test%20Guernsey%20health%20workers%262020-04-03T12%3A48%3A13.588Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:7d81def2-0f31-4629-b40a-c3da2406a7dd&pinned_post_asset_id=5e872febcfdb750670d9bdea&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nPositive cases are re-tested 14 days later or 48 hours after any symptoms have been resolved (whichever is latest).<ref>{{cite web |title=On-Island testing \u2013 an update |url=https://www.gov.gg/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=124347&p=0 |website=gov.gg |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> As of 11 April, 48 previously confirmed cases have been reported to be recovered;<ref name=\"test results\"/> acknowledging that there are various definitions of 'recovery' for the coronavirus, Dr Brink clarified that the States were using \"the virological definition with a repeat test on day 14 to show the virus has gone\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Thirteen people have recovered from virus in Guernsey |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e872adf4f63c606765ce42f%26Thirteen%20people%20have%20recovered%20from%20virus%20in%20Guernsey%262020-04-03T12%3A42%3A51.892Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:952d641c-f8ee-4a1e-b808-45c4d598eb6a&pinned_post_asset_id=5e872adf4f63c606765ce42f&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Results and analysis====\nAs of 12 April, 1,719 samples have been tested, yielding 218 positive results and 1,421 negative results with 80 results yet to be confirmed.<ref name=\"test results\">{{cite web |title=Testing results |url=https://covid19.gov.gg/test-results |website=gov.gg |date=20 March 2020 |publisher=States of Guernsey |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The actual number of cases is likely to be higher than the preceding figure due to the relatively low number of tests carried out.<ref name=\"higher\">{{cite journal |last1=Lau |first1=Hien |last2=Khosrawipour |first2=Veria |last3=Kocbach |first3=Piotr |last4=Mikolajczyk |first4=Agata |last5=Ichii |first5=Hirohito |last6=Schubert |first6=Justyna |last7=Bania |first7=Jacek |last8=Khosrawipour |first8=Tanja |title=Internationally lost COVID-19 cases |journal=Journal of Microbiology, Immunology and Infection |date=March 2020 |doi=10.1016/j.jmii.2020.03.013|pmid=32205091 |pmc=7102572 }}</ref>\n\nThe States of Guernsey has the capacity to test up to 75 samples per day (40 on-island and 35 through a UK laboratory), though this is subject to fast change.<ref>{{cite news |title=Capacity to test 'up to 75' Guernsey samples per day |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e84ae206d8c9806657fef20%26Capacity%20to%20test%20%27up%20to%2075%27%20Guernsey%20samples%20per%20day%262020-04-01T15%3A15%3A23.561Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:b6322065-5d28-4ffe-89f4-033274e8cbce&pinned_post_asset_id=5e84ae206d8c9806657fef20&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> St Pier has highlighted the relatively high number of tests being conducted in Guernsey as part of their strategy, noting that the island was testing 11.67 people per 100,000 population while the UK was only testing 2.46 per 100,000, which accounts for a relatively higher number of cases being identified.<ref>{{cite news |title=High levels of testing producing high levels of positives |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52084620?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e872ffc9cc871066e8594bc%26%27High%20levels%20of%20testing%20producing%20high%20levels%20of%20positives%27%262020-04-03T13%3A06%3A02.367Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:064061ba-f894-476e-bedb-480253cef3f2&pinned_post_asset_id=5e872ffc9cc871066e8594bc&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 12 April, the States of Guernsey have identified the UK, France, Tenerife, mainland Spain, Germany, Austria, Switzerland and Jersey as well as local transmissions, as sources of the infection in the Bailiwick.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jersey contact among latest confirmed cases |url=https://gsy.bailiwickexpress.com/gsy/news/jersey-contact-among-latest-confirmed-cases/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=gsy.bailiwickexpress.com |publisher=Bailiwick Express |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The age range of positive cases spanned from less than one-year-old to over 90 years old; the average age of patients was 56, with an average age of 57 for males and 54 for females.<ref name=\"3aprilgp\"/><ref name=\"test results\"/> As of 7 April, only 13 out of 166 confirmed cases have been from unidentified community seeding, with the majority of remaining cases coming from identified clusters.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thorn |first1=Rebecca |title=Thirteen cases from unidentified community seeding |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-europe-guernsey-52149479?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e8c5f25cfdb750670d9c412%26Thirteen%20cases%20from%20unidentified%20community%20seeding%262020-04-07T11%3A11%3A52.896Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:a3292053-9004-4b42-9c49-7c6286155c45&pinned_post_asset_id=5e8c5f25cfdb750670d9c412&pinned_post_type=share |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=bbc.co.uk |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:85%\"\n|+ style=\"font-size:117%;\" | COVID-19 testing statistics and deaths in Guernsey\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=50px | Date\n! colspan=\"2\" width=100px | Positive results\n! colspan=\"2\" width=100px | Deaths\n! colspan=\"2\" width=100px | Tests\n! colspan=\"2\" width=100px | Recoveries\n|-\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n|-\n| 9 Mar\n| 1\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| {{grey|\u2013}}\n| 84\n| {{grey|\u2013}}\n| {{grey|\u2013}}\n|-\n| \u22ee\n| colspan=\