011}}\n[[Category:Copa Libertadores Femenina seasons|2011]]\n[[Category:2011 in women's association football]]\n[[Category:2011 in South American football]]\n[[Category:2011 in Brazilian women's football|Lib]]\n[[Category:International club association football competitions hosted by Brazil]]\n[[Category:International women's association football competitions hosted by Brazil]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox international football competition\n| tourney_name = Copa Libertadores de F\u00fatbol Femenina\n| year = 2011\n| other_titles = \n| image =\n| size = \n| caption =\n| country = Brazil\n| dates = 13\u201327 November 2011\n| num_teams = 12\n| associations = 10\n| venues = 2\n| cities = 1\n| champion_other = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 Esporte Clube (women)|S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9]]\n| count = 1\n| second_other = {{flagicon|CHI}} [[Colo-Colo (women)|Colo Colo]]\n| third_other = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Santos FC (women)|Santos]]\n| fourth_other = {{flagicon|VEN|football}} [[Caracas FC|Caracas]]\n| matches = 22\n| goals = 94\n| attendance = \n| top_scorer = {{flagicon|VEN|football}} [[Ysaura Viso]] (9 goals)\n| player =\n| prevseason=[[2010 Copa Libertadores Femenina|2010]]\n| nextseason=[[2012 Copa Libertadores Femenina|2012]]\n}}\nThe '''2011 Copa Libertadores de F\u00fatbol Femenino''' was the third edition of the [[Copa Libertadores de F\u00fatbol Femenino]], CONMEBOL's premier annual international women's football club tournament. It was again held in Brazil from 13 to 27 November 2011.<ref name=bol>{{cite web|title=Gerimex Bolivian champion 2011 |url=http://www.facetasdeportivastv.com/nota.php?id=20157 |author=facetasdeportivastv.com |accessdate=6 September 2011 |language=Spanish |date=5 September 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017212000/http://facetasdeportivastv.com/nota.php?id=20157 |archivedate=17 October 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=La Libertadores Femenina 2011 se jugar\u00e1 del 13 al 27 de noviembre|url=http://www.conmebol.com/libertadoresfemenina/La-Libertadores-Femenina-2011-se-jugara-del-13-al-27-de-noviembre-20111004-0002.html|publisher=conmebol|accessdate=13 October 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref>  [[Santos FC (ladies)|Santos]] were the defending champions.\n\nThe competition was won by the local team [[S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 Esporte Clube (women)|S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9]] for the first time. Two time champion Santos finished in third place. Caracas' [[Ysaura Viso]] won the top-scorer award having scored nine goals in her teams five matches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Viso wins topscorer award|url=http://www.gradadigital.com/principal/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2294:ysaura-viso-emula-a-stalin-y-ruberth-goleadora-de-la-libertadores&catid=21:otras-categorias&Itemid=159|publisher=gradadigital.com|accessdate=1 December 2011|language=Portuguese|date=29 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Changes from 2010==\n*The tournament was expanded from 10 to 12 teams. This allows for Santos to enter and be able to defend the trophy. As well as a local team from the host city.<ref name=regulations>{{cite web|title=2011 announcement and regulations|url=http://www.conmebol.com/libertadoresfemenina/Copa-Santander-Libertadores-Femenina-habra-12-equipos-participantes-20111018-0002.html|publisher=CONMEBOL|accessdate=19 October 2011|language=Spanish|date=18 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\nThe twelve teams are divided in three groups of four. The teams then play each other once. After that the group winners and the best runner-up qualify for the semi-finals. Those as well as the final are single-legged, i.e. no home and away matches.<ref name=regulations />\n\n==Qualified teams==\nThere have been talks to expand the competition to 12 teams, give one spot to title holders Santos and one spot to the Japanese 2011 [[L. League]] champion.<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 tournament in Brazil|url=http://www.golfutgol.com/1031/brasil-volvera-a-ser-la-sede-de-copa-libertadores/|publisher=golfutgol.com|accessdate=12 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425062118/http://www.golfutgol.com/1031/brasil-volvera-a-ser-la-sede-de-copa-libertadores/|archive-date=2012-04-25|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref> Ultimately it was decided to give the twelfth spot to a local team of the host city.<ref name=regulations />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n!Association\n!Team\n!Qualifying method\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Argentine Football Association|Argentina]]\n|[[Boca Juniors#Women.27s football|Boca Juniors]]\n|2010\u201311 [[Campeonato de F\u00fatbol Femenino|Clausura and Apertura]] champions<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00a1Humillen, chicas!|url=http://www.ole.com.ar/boca-juniors/poli/Humillen-chicas_0_526747511.html|publisher=ole.com.ar|accessdate=6 September 2011|language=Spanish|date=30 July 2011|quote=qualified to Copa Libertadores 2nd year in a row}}</ref> \n|-\n|{{flagicon|BOL|football}} [[Bolivian Football Federation|Bolivia]]\n|[[Gerimex]] \n|2011 [[Bolivian women's football championship|Bolivian League]] champion<ref name=bol />\n|-\n|rowspan=3|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brazilian Football Confederation|Brazil]]\n|[[CEPE-Caxias]]\n|[[2010 Copa do Brasil de Futebol Feminino]] champion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssfbrasil.com/tablesae/cbr2010w.htm|title=Brazil Women's Cup 2010|year=2010|accessdate=22 April 2011|publisher=[[RSSSF]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Santos FC (ladies)|Santos]]\n|[[2010 Copa Libertadores Femenina|Title holder]]<ref name=regulations />\n|-\n|[[S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 Esporte Clube (women)|S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9]]\n|Host city team<ref name=regulations />\n|-\n|{{flagicon|CHI}} [[Football Federation of Chile|Chile]]\n|[[Colo-Colo (women)|Colo Colo]]\n|2010 [[Chilean women's football championship|Chilean League]] champion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anfp.cl/detalle_noticia.php?noticia=9050|title=Colo Colo was crowned in women's football|publisher=anfp.cl|year=2010|accessdate=22 April 2010|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231044009/http://www.anfp.cl/detalle_noticia.php?noticia=9050|archive-date=2010-12-31|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|COL}} [[Colombian Football Federation|Colombia]]\n|[[Club Deportivo Formas \u00cdntimas|Formas \u00cdntimas]]\n|won play-off match (no national league)<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Formas manager|url=http://mundodelfutbolfemenino.blogspot.com/2011/10/conmebol-un-modelo-en-sudamerica.html|publisher=mundodelfutbolfemenino.blogspot.com|accessdate=18 November 2011|language=Spanish|date=30 October 2011|quote=Confederation set up a play-off against Sarmiento Lora.}}</ref> \n|-\n|{{flagicon|ECU}} [[Ecuadorian Football Federation|Ecuador]]\n|[[Liga Deportiva Universitaria de Quito|LDU Quito]]\n|2010 Copa Credif\u00e9 femenina champion<ref>{{cite web|title=Liga de Quito debuts in Copa Libertadores|url=http://www.eltiempo.com.ec/noticias-cuenca/83180-liga-de-quito-debuta-en-la-libertadores-femenina/|publisher=eltiempo.com.ec|accessdate=18 November 2011|language=Spanish|date=14 November 2011|quote=LDU gained entry by winning the 2010 Copa Credif\u00e9 femenina}}</ref> \n|-\n|{{flagicon|PAR}} [[Paraguayan Football Association|Paraguay]]\n|[[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Asunci\u00f3n (football)|Universidad Aut\u00f3noma]]\n|2010 [[Paraguayan women's football championship|Paraguayan League]] champion<ref>{{cite web|title=Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Asunci\u00f3n undefeated champion|url=http://mundodelfutbolfemenino.blogspot.com/2011/08/paraguay-apertura-femenino-uaa-campeon.html|publisher=mundodelfutbolfemenino.blogspot.com|accessdate=6 September 2011|language=Spanish|date=28 August 2011}}</ref> \n|-\n|{{flagicon|PER|football}} [[Peruvian Football Federation|Peru]]\n|[[JC Sport Girls]]\n|2011 [[Peruvian women's football championship|Campeonato Nacional de F\u00fatbol Femenino]] champion<ref>{{cite web|title=UAA starts preparing for tourney|url=http://mundodelfutbolfemenino.blogspot.com/2011/10/libertadores-femenina-uaa-se-apresta.html|publisher=mundodelfutbolfemenino.blogspot.com|accessdate=17 October 2011|language=Spanish|format=17 October 2011}}</ref> \n|-\n|{{flagicon|URU}} [[Uruguayan Football Association|Uruguay]]\n|[[Club Nacional de Football|Nacional]]\n|2010 [[Campeonato Uruguayo Femenino]] champion<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.de/translate?hl=de&sl=auto&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.futbol.com.uy%2Fnotdeportes_127203_1.html|title=National champion in women's football|date=22 December 2010|publisher=futbol.com.uy}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|VEN|football}} [[Venezuelan Football Federation|Venezuela]]\n|[[Caracas FC|Caracas]]\n|2011 [[Venezuelan women's football championship|Venezuelan League]] champions<ref>{{cite web|title=venezuela \u2013 feminas del caracas fc ya son tricampeonas|trans-title=Women of FC Caracas are three time champion.|url=http://mundodelfutbolfemenino.blogspot.com/2011/06/venezuela-feminas-del-caracas-fc-ya-son.html|accessdate=13 June 2011|language=Spanish|date=11 June 2011}}</ref>\n|}\n\nEach team was allowed to nominate 20 players for the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Team Squads|url=http://www.conmebol.com/libertadoresfemenina/Copa-Libertadores-Femenina-2011-listas-de-jugadoras-20111112-0001.html|publisher=CONMEBOL|accessdate=17 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==First stage==\nThe group winner and the best runners-up advanced to the semifinals. The draw and fixtures were announced on 1 November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fixtures|url=http://www.conmebol.com/libertadoresfemenina/Libertadores-femenina-2011-Fixture-20111031-0006.html|publisher=CONMEBOL|accessdate=1 November 2011|language=Spanish|date=1 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|Key to colors in group tables\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#cfc; width:20px;\"|\n|align=left|Group winners and runners-up advanced to the semi-finals\n|}\n\nTie-breaker in case of equal points is:\n# Goal difference\n# Goals scored\n# Match between tied teams\nIf still tied the organisers may decide how to proceed. In case two team are tied after having played each other the last matchday, the tie is decided by a penalty shootout.\n\n===Group A===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!width=165 |Team\n!width=20 |{{Tooltip| Pld | Played}}\n!width=20 |{{Tooltip| W | Won}}\n!width=20 |{{Tooltip| D | Drawn}}\n!width=20 |{{Tooltip| L | Lost}}\n!width=20 |{{Tooltip| GF | Goals for}}\n!width=20 |{{Tooltip| GA | Goals against}}\n!width=25 |{{Tooltip| GD | Goal difference}}\n!width=20 |{{Tooltip| Pts | Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#cfc;\"\n|align=left|{{flagicon|CHI}} [[Colo-Colo (women)|Colo Colo]]\n| 3 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 9 || 3 || +6 || '''7'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap|{{flagicon|PAR}} [[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Asunci\u00f3n (football)|Universidad Aut\u00f3noma]]}}\n| 3 || 1 || 2 || 0 || 7 || 3 || +4 || '''5'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[CEPE-Caxias]]\n| 3 || 1 || 1 || 1 || 5 || 2 || +3 || '''4'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|PER|football}} [[JC Sport Girls]]\n| 3 || 0 || 0 || 3 || 1 || 14 || \u221213 || '''0'''\n|}\n\n{{footballbox\n|date = 13 November 2011\n|time = 10:00 [[UTC\u221202:00]]\n|team1 = [[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Asunci\u00f3n (football)|Universidad Aut\u00f3noma]] {{flagicon|PAR}}\n|score = 2\u20132\n|report = [http://mundodelfutbolfemenino.blogspot.com/2011/11/uruguay-es-el-dia-este-lunes-la-hora.html Report]\n|team2 = {{flagicon|CHI}} [[Colo-Colo (women)|Colo Colo]]\n|goals1 =  [[Noelia Cuevas|N. Cuevas]] {{goal|46}}<br> [[Dulce Quintana|Quintana]] {{goal|78}}\n|goals2 = [[B\u00e1rbara Santib\u00e1\u00f1ez|Santib\u00e1\u00f1ez]] {{goal|32}}<br> [[Nathalie Quezada|Quezada]] {{goal|50|pen}}\n|stadium = [[Est\u00e1dio ADC Parahyba]], [[S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 dos Campos]]\n|attendance = 100\n|referee = \n}}\n{{footballbox\n|date = 13 November 2011\n|time = 12:15 [[UTC\u221202:00]]\n|team1 = [[CEPE-Caxias]] {{flagicon|BRA}} \n|score = 4\u20130\n|report = [http://mundodelfutbolfemenino.blogspot.com/2011/11/uruguay-es-el-